28. Africanum: Cn. Domitius AhenobarbuS, one of the partizans of MariuS, had escaped to Africa and formed an alliance with Hiar- baS, the pretender to the throne of Numidia. Pompey defeated Ahenobarbus in 81 B.c., and within forty days put an end to all opposition in Africa. For this victory a triumph was granted him, although he had not yet risen to senatorial rank. Up to this time only magistrates with the imperium (dictator, consul, praetor) had been allowed to celebrate a triumph—Transalpinam: while on his march to Spain in 77 B.C., Pompey had to contend in several fierce engagements with Gallie tribeS, which had probably been in- duced by Sertorius to dispute his passage. —Hispaniense z see note on p. 126, l. 3o.—mixtum ex . . . nationibus: in reference to the motley character of the forces of Sertorius.
